<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-04-16T11:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-04-16T11:00:00-05:00" n="186" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d186">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 European War 1939/2476:
                                Telegram</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador to the Yugoslav Government in
                                    Exile</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">MacVeagh</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Cairo</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-04-16T19:00:00+03:00">April
                                        16, 1944—7 p.m.</date>
                                    <lb/> [Received April 17—5:30 a.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>Yugos 92. See my Yugos 90 of April 14, 6 p.m. Lord Moyne advises me
                                that Russian Ambassador asked to see him urgently this afternoon and
                                informed him that 2 or 3 days ago he had transmitted to Moscow a
                                suggestion of Stirbey that if Antonescu does not take action and if
                                Maniu cannot overthrow him Maniu should transfer himself to Russian
                                territory in Moldavia and establish a government in opposition to
                                Antonescu, the same conditions being granted to Maniu in this event
                                as those set forth in my Yugos 84 of April 8, 2 p.m. Novikov added
                                that Moscow has now approved that this proposal be made to Maniu on
                                condition that London and Washington also agree.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">MacVeagh</hi>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>